        },


```

Some pseudocode to illustrate an issue:

```javascript
// Let's imagine we have a state tree with this structure
{
    state: {},
    modules: {
        module1: {
            state: {
                 data: { subItem: 'value' }
            }
        }
    }
}

// Pass the same nested value (at least from the second level relative to the module) to the action
const testSequence = [
    testAction(
        state.module1.data.subItem, 
        moduleState.data.subItem
    )
];

// Full-path variant is resolved, moduleState variant is undefined
function testAction(param1, param2) {
     return ({ get }) => {
         console.log(get(param1)); // 'value'
         console.log(get(param2)); // undefined
     }
}
```

p.s.: I've found that issue a year ago and decided to not use moduleState until it fixed, but it looks like nobody else notice it :)
